   "source": [
    "# Outlier generation\n",
    "\n",
    "Wildboar is bundled with support for outlier detection. The primary focus is on detecting samples that deviate from what is expected, i.e., outlier samples, as opposed to detecting deviating patterns or time points. Since there are no good benchmark datasets for outlier detection (except for ``wildboar/outlier``), we support the constructing outlier datasets from traditional classification tasks."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pylab as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier\n",
    "from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline\n",
    "\n",
    "from wildboar.datasets import load_dataset\n",
    "from wildboar.datasets.outlier import (\n",
    "    kmeans_outliers,\n",
    "    majority_outliers,\n",
    "    minority_outliers,\n",
    "    density_outliers,\n",
    "    emmott_outliers,\n",
    ")\n",
    "from wildboar.embed import IntervalEmbedding\n",
    "from wildboar.utils import plot"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x, y = load_dataset(\"GunPoint\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_inlier_outlier(x_outlier, y_outlier):\n",
    "    label, value = np.unique(y_outlier, return_counts=True)\n",
    "    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "    gs = plt.GridSpec(2, 2, figure=fig)\n",
    "    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :])\n",
    "    ax1.set_title(\"Projection\")\n",
    "    plot_projection(x_outlier, y_outlier, ax=ax1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0])\n",
    "    ax2.set_title(\"Distribution\")\n",
    "    ax2.bar(label, value, color=plt.cm.get_cmap(\"Dark2\", 2).colors)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax3 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 1])\n",
    "    ax3.set_title(\"Time series\")\n",
    "    plot.plot_time_domain(x_outlier, y=y_outlier, ax=ax3)\n",
    "    fig.tight_layout()\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_projection(x_outlier, y_outlier, ax=None):\n",
    "    if ax is None:\n",
    "        fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "\n",
    "    pipe = make_pipeline(IntervalEmbedding(n_interval=15), PCA(2, random_state=123))\n",
    "    projection = pipe.fit_transform(x_outlier, y_outlier)\n",
    "    cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap(\"Dark2\", 2)\n",
    "    ax.scatter(\n",
    "        projection[y_outlier == 1, 0],\n",
    "        projection[y_outlier == 1, 1],\n",
    "        marker=\"x\",\n",
    "        color=cmap(0),\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    ax.scatter(\n",
    "        projection[y_outlier == -1, 0],\n",
    "        projection[y_outlier == -1, 1],\n",
    "        marker=\"x\",\n",
    "        color=cmap(1),\n",
    "    )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Minority labeler\n",
    "\n",
    "The minority labeler defines the outlier class as the minority class of the training samples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_outlier, y_outlier = minority_outliers(x, y, n_outliers=None)\n",
    "plot_inlier_outlier(x_outlier, y_outlier)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For a balanced dataset, the minority sampler fails to simulate outliers and inliers. As such, the user can specify a fraction of the resulting dataset that should be outliers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_outlier, y_outlier = minority_outliers(x, y, n_outliers=0.07)\n",
    "plot_inlier_outlier(x_outlier, y_outlier)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Majority labeler\n",
    "\n",
    "Another option is to simply consider the minority class as iniliers and then draw a (small) sample of the majority class and consider those as outliers. Compared to the minority labeler, this method is generally more suitable for generating outliers from multiclass problems."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_outlier, y_outlier = majority_outliers(x, y, n_outliers=0.05)\n",
    "plot_inlier_outlier(x_outlier, y_outlier)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## KMeans labeler\n",
    "\n",
    "A sligtly more refined approach is to construct k-clusters and and consider the cluster with the centroid farthest from the other clusters as the outlier label.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_outlier, y_outlier = kmeans_outliers(x, n_outliers=0.05, n_clusters=20)\n",
    "plot_inlier_outlier(x_outlier, y_outlier)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Density labeler\n",
    "\n",
    "Another approach is to consider density based clustering, and assign those samples which do not belong to a cluster as the outliers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_outlier, y_outlier = density_outliers(x, y, n_outliers=0.05, eps=2)\n",
    "plot_inlier_outlier(x_outlier, y_outlier)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## EmottLabeler"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_outlier, y_outlier = emmott_outliers(x, y, n_outliers=0.05, difficulty=\"simplest\")\n",
    "plot_inlier_outlier(x_outlier, y_outlier)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x432 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2,  figsize=(12, 6))\n",
    "ax = ax.flatten()\n",
    "for i, difficulty in enumerate([1, 2, 3, [3, 4]]):\n",
    "    x_outlier, y_outlier = emmott_outliers(\n",
    "        x,\n",
    "        y,\n",
    "        n_outliers=0.1,\n",
    "        variation=\"dispersed\",\n",
    "        difficulty=difficulty,\n",
    "        random_state=123,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    plot_projection(x_outlier, y_outlier, ax=ax[i])\n",
    "    ax[i].set_title(\"Difficulty: %s\" % str(difficulty))\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.tight_layout()"
   ]
  }
 ],
